column168: On July 8, 2013, it was noticed that a 55 gallon drum of NA1760 Compound Cleaning Liquid containing Sodium Hydroxide located on an R&L Carriers tractor-trailer had an apparent puncture and was tipped over inside the trailer. An estimated 50 gallons of material released to the interior of the trailer and onto the gravel/asphalt lot. Midwest Environmental Personnel responded to the scene to secure and contain the release. Midwest Personnel applied citric acid to neutralize the material. They then utilized a vacuum truck to collect all free standing liquids. Citric acid was applied along with absorbents to the interior of the trailer, then collected and containerized for pending disposal.

column168: At approximately 7:00 P.M. on Monday July 8, 2013 tank car PROX 73226 was inspected by FRA in the KCS Artesia Yard in Artesia, MS. It was noted by the FRA inspector that all 6 manway bolts were significantly less than tool tight thus resulting in a non-accident release. Appropriate notifications were made to all parties involved. The car was spotted on a siding for a response team to arrive another day to clean up residue on the side of the car and to secure tank car appurtenances.     On Wednesday July 10, 2013 a response crew arrived at the Artesia to clean and secure the car. Upon further investigation it was discovered that not only were the manway bolts loose but there was no manway gasket present either. The response team installed a new, compatible manway gasket and secured a manway bolts tool tight. The released lading was cleaned and the car released into transportation    * No injuries reported    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence.   It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. To improve communications the shipper can provide contact information in this web site (Contact Network) to better facilitate incident response and post incident communications as applicable.

column168: An inbound BNSF intermodal train's mechanical inspection in the railyard revealed intermodal trailer RDWY 280994 leaking an unknown liquid substance. The entrained intermodal flatcar that RDWY 280994 was atop was set-out of the train. RDWY 280994 was removed from its railcar and carefully moved to a containment/dock area for further inspection. Contract responders reported insufficient blocking and bracing allowed interior load shifting of the lading within RDWY 280994. Seven 5 gallon steel pails containing resin materials were found damaged and had leaked. Most of these pails were near empty due to dent punctures and cuts in these pail's sidewalls. The damaged pails were removed from the lading and earmarked for appropriate disposal. Spillage inside RDWY 280994 was cleaned and all removed non-damaged lading was returned inside RDWY 280994 properly blocked and braced for further transportation. Spillage on the exterior of RDWY 280994 was also noted as being cleaned.
column169: Ensure shipper's hazardous material LTL shipments are properly blocked and braced to avoid lading damage during normal transportation.

column168: On July 2, 2013 at 19:19 hours, MC Bethge, CSX Manager of Hazardous Material System-Field Services was notified by FRA Hazardous Material Inspector Donald Tetterton during his yard inspection at Kenmore Yard, Tonawanda, NY, he found SRIX 30076, a loaded tank car of UN1268, Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S., a class 3 flammable liquid to be venting vapors from the VRD, Vacuum Relief Device Valve. The tank car was isolated and the shipper Calumet Specialty, Inc. was notified by CHEMTREC, report #2013-07-02-0030. Joshua Maynard, Cell 317-500-3981 the Calumet representative was notified of the situation. A CSXT contractor, EP+S of VT the Buffalo, NY office was called to respond, investigate and handle the incident. EP+S VT found the VRD identified by FRA HM Tetterton. The VRD was removed and a blind closure plug was installed to stop the vapor release.  Calumet Specialty, Inc. applied for an OTMA-3 to move SRIX 30076 to destination for unloading and will home shop the tank car upon residue status. OTMA-3 applied July 16, 2013, E.P. Rudolph, FRA-RSS-HM approved.    This tank car did not require a special switch move.  An AAR 7.1 form will be filed for the VRD (Valve).    Cause Code: 466  NARRI: 2x(5+3+0)x(2x0) = 60
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: On July 4, 2013 at 03:34 hours, a car inspector at the CSXT Osborn Yard, Louisville, Kentucky noticed a slight odor near GATX 51958, a loaded tank car of UN1005, Anhydrous Ammonia. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, Terra International Canada Inc., was notified via direct phone number as stated on the waybill emergency contact section (519) 867-2739. Summit Contracting, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Osborn Yard. Summit found the "A" end liquid line valve with a slight leak. The secondary closure plug was found in a less than tool tight condition. The secondary securement plug was partially loosened to allow the installation of thread sealant and then tightened tool tight. This secured the tank car and stopped all release of product. The shipper representative, Bill Deshamps (519) 490-1811 was notified of the situation found. The release was secured and GATX 51958 is currently awaiting FRA "One Time Movement Approval" prior to the release for disposition after the "A" end liquid line valve was deemed to be faulty and not in proper working condition.    This incident did require a special move.    NARRI: 5x(5+10+2)x(2+0) = 170  Cause code:120

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car UTLX 952325 was reported venting from its reclosing pressure relief device (PRD) in the railyard. UTLX 952325 was in queue awaiting placement for unloading at the nearby consignee's facility. The ambient temperature was at or near 115 degrees F at this time. Local F.D. responders using LEL metering devices reported that the vapor being released was confined at the protective housing cover of UTLX 952325. No other securement issues were noted. UTLX 952325 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard for commodity reduction. A shipper/consignee representative arranged to transload approximately 2500 gallons of commodity from UTLX 952325 into tank truck to allow additional vapor space within UTLX 952325. After this was accomplished without further incident, the venting from the PRD (Midland A-35280, 280.5 psig) ceased.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous material at Clean Harbors Laurel MD facility was being loaded with intransit drums for continued transportation to the  intended waste disposal facility. While transferring the drum the operator of the forklift punctured the drum with the fork of the forklift. A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and over packed the leaking drum. The trailer floor and containment area was cleaned with a cleaning compound and packed into the over pack then returned to service for continued transport to intended disposal facility. The Maryland Department of Environment was notified of release and the NRC due to the RQ of the material.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. Loading and tranfer procedures with forklift are being reviewed with operator of this incident and all facility personell.

The impacted area was neutralized and absorbents were worked in. All contaminated material was collected and containerized for pending disposal.

While loading a shipment of hazardous waste at the shipper's location, the driver heard a noise from the pump while watching the level gauge which did not show full.  He turned off the pump but some material overflowed from his bucket under the valve.  The plant personnel cleaned up the material which overflowed the bucket onto the ground, removing 2 shovelfuls of dirt in the process.  The cleanup material was placed into a salvage container and left at the plant.  The loading was completed and the shipment proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.

column169: We have changed from bungees to a much stronger material velcro type strap.  Also we are putting together some training programs to better educate our drivers as to what to look for when it comes to our preventative measures to stop these types of spills happening.

column169: Properly prepare any engine parts for transportation, securing any ports and drain any unnecessary fluids to prevent any leakage. column168: Friday the 12th, after the drum was picked up and brought to our facility, a driver came up to me and let me know that the drum didn't have any placards on it, but was marked as Hazmat in the computer. So I kept the drum on the dock until we could identify why it wasn't marked correctly. Monday afternoon I looked and found out that the drum was filled with UN1405 Calcium Silicide (or Silicon), 4.3 Dangerous When Wet. I ended up putting placards on the drum and saw that there were small solid chunks of the chemical along with dust surrounding the lid of the drum. I knew there wasn't a leak in the lid because the bungholes were secured and the handle for the lid was secured. I could only assume the chemical spilled over at the shipper's warehouse. On the lid of the drum there are about 3 small pieces of solid chemical, along with dust surrounding the lid, totaling maybe 6 grams of chemical. The company that was contracted to clean up the spill was HazChem, called by ERTS (Emergency Response & Training Solutions). The company should have it cleaned by 0700 on Tuesday morning (the 16th).
column169: The first step in the prevention process would be for the company/shipper to ensure their shipments are fully placarded, with no residual chemicals on the outside. The next step is to ensure our drivers fully examine all Hazmat shipments to make sure they are marked correctly, and the documentation is accurate, otherwise it should not be picked up. Finally, to coach all the drivers to be vigilant in making sure their Hazmat shipments are correct so that the safety of everyone involved is maintained at the highest levels.

column168: AN IRREG SORTER WAS MOVING A PAIL ACROSS THE ROLLERS OF THE IRREG BELT WHEN THE LID BECAME LOOSE & POWDER BEGAN TO COME OUT OF THE PAIL HE IMMEDIATELY MOVED AWAY FROM THE AREA & NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR, WHO CALLED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED AT THE AREA I SAW A YELLOW OXIDIZER DIAMOND LABEL ON THE SIDE OF THE PAIL USED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS (OXIDIZER) TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. CONTAINERIZED THE PAIL TO A LINED SPILL TRAY, I SWEPT UP THE LOOSE POWDER & PUT IT INTO ANOTHER LINED SPILL TRAY BECAUSE I COULD STILL SEE BITS OF THE POWDER CAUGHT IN THE ROLLERS, I PUT SOME CLAY-BASED ABSORBANT ON THE ROLLERS TO HELP SWEEP UP THE LAST BIT, SWEPT UP THE ABSORBANT/POWDER MIXTURE & ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TRAY. ONCE I WAS ASSURED THAT ALL POWDER HAD BEEN SWEPT UP, I TOOK THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I EXAMINED THE PAIL, I FOUND THAT THE LID HAD SIMPLY COME LOOSE.

column168: FOUR PORTABLE TANKS OF THE SAME MATERIAL WERE LOADED AT THE GENERATOR'S SITE. ONE OF THE TOTES WAS NOTICED TO HAVE OBVIOUS INTEGRITY ISSUES WHICH INCLUDED CRACKS IN THE TOTE BLADDER POSSIBLY AS A RESULT OF UV DAMAGE TO THE POLY. IT DID NOT APPEAR THE WASTE MATERIAL IN THE COMPROMISED TANK WAS TRANSFERRED TO AN EMPTY TANK (PROVIDED BY THE GENERATOR) THAT WAS INSPECTED BY THE E2 FIELD SERVICE CREW AND BELIEVED TO BE IN SOUND CONDITION. THE CONTAINER THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO HAD ALL THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS AND RATINGS PER 49 CFR 178 FOR THE TYPE OF MATERIAL BEING TRANSPORTED.  THE REST OF THE WASTE CONTAINERS WERE LOADED, SECURED AND THE VEHICLE DEPARTED FOR ITS INTERIM DESTINATION (MESQUITE TERMINAL) EN ROUTE TO ITS FINAL DESTINATION - RINECO CHEMICAL-BENTON,AR. WITHIN A COUPLE OF HOURS ON THE HIGHWAY, UPON DISCOVERING THE NATURE OF THE INCIDENT, THE DRIVER PULLED THE VEHICLE OFF THE ROAD, E2 MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED, AND THE CLEANUP PROCESS BEGAN IMMEDIATELY. WHEN INSPECTED, THE TANK BLADDER HAD CRACKED AND CHIPPED IN SEVERAL PLACES, CAUSING LOSS OF MATERIAL. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT <100 GALLONS OF A FLAMMABLE LIQUID MIXTURE WAS DISCHARGED TO THE HIGHWAY OVER AN AREA OF APPROXIMATELY 20 MILES. THE REST OF THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK STAYED EITHER IN THE TANK OR WERE CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER. IT DOES NOT APPEAR THAT ANY OF THE MATERIAL MIGRATED OFF THE HIGHWAY SURFACE AND INTO ANY SURFACE WATERS. THE MATERIAL MAY HAVE JUST BEEN ABSORBED INTO THE PAVEMENT, BUT MOST LIKELY EVAPORATED.  TWO CREWS OF HAZ MAT RESPONDERS WERE NOTIFIED AND CLEANUP TOOK PLACE ON THE SITE THE TRUCK WAS PULLED OVER. THE INITIAL INCIDENT HAPPENED AROUND 5:00PM AND THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETE AND THE TRUCK WAS MOVED TO A SECURED LOCATION BY 10:00PM. A FULL INVESTIGATION OF THE INCIDENT IS ONGOING, AND ONCE MOST OF THE PERTINENT DETAILS WERE OBTAINED, THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE EVENT AT APPROXIMATELY 12:00PM ON 11 JULY. THE ASSIGNED REPORT NUMBER FOR THE EVENT IS 1053469.  THERE WERE REPORTS THAT SEVERAL VEHICLES WERE CONTAMINATED WITH THE WASTE MATERIAL. WE HAVE NOTIFIED ANYONE THAT HAS CONTACTED US TO TAKE PROPER MEASURES TO CLEAN/REPAIR THEIR VEHICLES AND WE WILL REIMBURSE THEIR EXPENSE. OUR INSURANCE COMPANY HAS BEEN NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. WE WILL MODIFY/UPDATE THIS REPORT AS MORE INFORMATION BECOMES AVAILABLE OR EVIDENCE IS DETERMINED TO CONFLICT ANYTHING STATED EARLIER IN THE REPORT.
column169: WE WILL MODIFY OUR POLICY ON ACCEPTANCE OF PORTABLE TANKS FOR SHIPMENT BY PROVIDING NEW, PROPERLY UN RATED, COMPATIBLE CONTAINERS FOR HAZ MAT SHIPMENTS AND REQUIRE CUSTOMERS TO USE THESE CONTAINERS FOR SHIPMENT OR VERIFY BEFORE OFFERING FOR SHIPMENT, THAT THE CONTAINERS ARE PROPERLY RATED FOR THE MATERIAL AND ARE IN GOOD CONDITION FOR SHIPMENT. WE ARE ALSO IMPLEMENTING A MORE INTENSE TRAINING PROGRAM TO SPECIFICALLY COVER 49 CFR 178 TO ENSURE CONTAINERS ARE COMPATIBLE AND SECURE FOR HAZ MAT SHIPMENTS. THIS NEW TRAINING PROGRAM WILL GO BEYOND THE CURRENT DOT REQUIREMENTS TO ADDRESS THESE ISSUES.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: A FRA Railroad Safety Inspector inspecting railcars in the railyard reported residue tank car SHPX 204947 venting vapor at the liquid line's bolted pipe flange connection that had 2 of 4 of its flange bolt stud nuts less than tool tight. Also, the liquid line's closure plug was identified as less than tool tight. In addition, the vapor line's pipe flange connection was identified with 1 of 4 flange bolt stud nuts being less than tool tight. These securement deficiencies were reported to local BNSF mechanical personnel whom proceeded to tool tighten these loose nuts and closure plug. Afterwards, the vapor vent ebbed but continued at the liquid line's flange connection. Contract responders identified the liquid line's pipe flange gasket as being partially torn and rolled, not sealing. The responders removed the defective flange gasket and applied Gore-Tex gasket material at the flange connection to seal the liquid line's flange connection. The flange connection was resecured and no further vapor release was detectable.  SHPX 204947 was forwarded to qualified repair facility per OTMA FRA-13070481.

column168: At 13:10 hours on 7/24/13 Knoche yard reported that a train crew detected a strong odor emitting from tank car CBTX 741391. The car is a load of Petroleum Crude Oil UN1267 Class 3. All concerned were notified and responder activated.    Responder arrived onsite at 1:45pm. Completed car shop safety briefing at 1:53pm. Air quality at the car shop was assessed and found to be safe (0% LEL, 0 ppb VOC 10.6 lamp, and ND H2S color metric tube). The tracks were blue flagged at 2:10pm. Began tank car investigation at 2:15 pm. Upon arriving tank car location, responder found safe air quality at ground level breathing zone (0% LEL, 20-40 ppb VOC, and ND H2S). There was a light detectable olfactory odor. The side of the tank car had evidence of released and volatilized (dried) lading.     Upon investigation of tank car top platform, found air quality in the breathing zone safe (0% LEL, 20-60,000 ppb VOC, and ND H2S). The manway was found to be leaking and had released approximately 1.0 gallon of lading account one loose manway bolt. The manway gasket was inspected and the gasket was found to be in satisfactory condition. It was determined that the manway was probably tightened incorrectly with a pneumatic impact wrench without the proper cross pattern sequence and thus caused the manway to lift on one side and not to position correctly. Responders properly closed and secured the manway and secured it tool tight. All other closures were inspected on this car and the following defects were found and corrected: Loose sample valve secondary closure plug (no release). Unsecured vapor valve secondary closure cap (no release).     Seal 119195 was removed from the manway, and replaced with HMRI606 + HMRI977.  Seal 119196 was removed from the protective housing, and replaced with HMRI700.    The tank car was released back into transportation at 5:30pm and the car shop and transportation department were so advised.    * No injuries reported  File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.   File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence.

column168: Driver was traveling Westbound on US Hwy. 40 at MP 26.  This is a downhill, winding stretch of 2 lane highway with passing lanes for uphill traffic.  According to the on board recoding device (CADEC), he was traveling 61mph moments before the rollover, then directly before it was at 58mph.  The speed limit at this location is 60mph.    Driver states after rounding a right hand bend in the hwy. he noticed the back axle of the pup leave the pavement, he tried to correct it but it continued off the pavement.  He further states he felt the steering wheel shanking as he continued to try to steer and slow down, when through the dust he saw the tongue of the draw bar separate from the lead trailer. He began to lose air for braking and was able to stop the truck 100 ft. down the road.    He got out of the cab and discovered the pup had overturned and was lying on its left side, in the downhill lane of traffic. He tried to call 911 and McRae Dispatch but his cell phone had a weak signal. A bystander continued to the top of Daniels Pass and contacted Emergency Services and McRae Dispatch. UHP and Wasatch County Sheriff's were dispatched to the scene, along with Park City Towing. D&A McRae Management responded immediately to the scene. Chevron Manager Anna Wilkins was also notified of the incident.    Upon arrival, D & A McRae personnel proceeded to off load the crude oil from the overturned pup (P13) to Truck 15. This was accomplished without incident. As a precaution, the product from the lead trailer that was part of the accident (T13) was also transferred. The load was delivered to the Chevron SLC Refinery that evening. Truck 10 and T13 were inspected on scene by the Roosevelt Shop Manager to ensure the units were road worthy.  It was driven fron the scene back to the Roosevelt Terminal. P13 was towed from the scene. No crude oil was spilled as a result of the overturn or from the transfer of the product.
column169: Observations on drivers will be re-doubled with continued focus on new drivers, driving skills, good decision making and recognizing risk.  Safety Meetings will be held this incident will be the focus.  We will discuss the Root causes of this incident and ways to avoid the complacency trap, rollover prevention and mountain driving.

column168: On July 11th, 2013, CSXT car department inspector at the CSXT Buffalo Frontier Yard, discovered CBTX 740319, a loaded tank car of UN 1267, Petroleum Crude Oil, to have wetness down the side of the tank car, the tank car was isolated, the shipper Great Northern Gathering, DBA  Watco Companies, 24 hour contact Eric Leigland at 406-478-9434. A CSXT emergency response was called, EP+S of Vermont  Buffalo office responded to investigate.  EP+S VT found the TODO Quick Connect valve seeping oil, the quick connect plunger has a weak spring and crude oil seeped. Crude Oil was padded out of the TODO Quick Connect and the tank car was wiped down. CSXT Hazmat Manager Michael Bethge inspected the TODO Quick Connect, and in discussion with Watco Companies determined that the TODO Quick Connect appears to have a defect plunger spring for proper sealing. Watco Companies is shipping a replacement TODO Quick Connect valve.    Cause Code: 310  NARRI: 2x(5+3+0)x(2+0) = 32

column168: On July 17th, 2013 at 19:15 hours, Q36417 was traveling eastbound through the interlocking limits of CP-437, crossing over from track 2 to track 1, when the last three railcars of the consist derailed. The last car of the train, DBUX 3021612, a loaded tank car of UN 1170, Ethyl Alcohol derailed and came to rest on its B-L side. During the derailment, the bottom outlet valve nozzle was sheared off, one of the mounting stub impacted the BOV locking ring causing a drip release of product. The Buffalo Fire Department HazMat Team place a containment pool under the drip. CSXT HazMat Manager Michael Bethge, and CSXT emergency response contractor EP+S of Vermont responded, using epoxy putty and a magnet patch, the drip release was secured. The car DBUX 302161 was re-railed at 0420 hours on 07/18/2013; it was moved to the CSX Transflo terminal in Buffalo, a distance of 2500 feet from the derailment site, where it was staged for a transfer.  On July 25th, 2013, the DBUX 302161 product load was transferred into PLMX 37751 by EP+S of Vermont, with the shipper Lyondell-Basell representatives on site for the process, DBUX 302161 will be cleaned + purged of all residue product and it will be a load-up for home shop repair. An OTMA-3 will be applied for once the load-up is completed.

column168: On 7/18/2013, at approximately 0300 the DG spill team was called to investigate a shipment in the primary, located at DHL Express  236 Wendall H. Ford Blvd, Erlanger, KY  41018.  Upon investigation there was found a shipment containing 3 inner containers.  One of the bottles was emitting smoke.  Tracking indicates initial transportation by air.  The MSDS and other documentation with the shipment specifically stated the product was a “Heat Transfer Fluid” identified as Dimethylphthalate and was not regulated per the IATA regulations.  The shipment was placed into a steel metal drum and set up for disposal.  The disposal team arrived to transfer the shipment to their facility for disposal.  When the shipment was removed from the steel drum, it immediately began smoking.  The disposal team contacted the intended receiver and was told the true identity of the product was Titanium Chloride, a regulated substance that must be kept cool to prevent from smoking.  The receiver also advised the two other bottles contained Benzodioxole, also a regulated substance.

The tote appeared to have leaked due to the temperature change which built pressure in the tote.  The material was released to the dock floor at the R&L Carriers terminal. column168: THE OPERATOR WAS LOADING 68% PHOSPHORIC ACID INTO RAIL CAR. HE FAILED TO CHECK TO SEE IF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS CLOSED. THE OPERATOR PLACED THE LOADING SPOUT ONTO THE MAN WAY ON THE CAR AND TURNED ON THE LOADING PUMP. ABOUT 25 MINUTES INTO THE LOADING PROCESS HE WENT STEPPED OUT OF THE CONTROL ROOM AND NOTICED ACID ON THE GROUND. ONE OPERATOR SHUT THE SYSTEM DOWN AND THE OTHER CLOSED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ON THE CAR AND STOPPED THE LEAK.
column169: THE OPERATOR DID NOT FOLLOW ESTABLISHED LOADING PROCEDURES. HE FAILED TO MAKE SURE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS CLOSED AND SECURED. HE ALSO DID NOT CHECK FOR LEAKS RIGHT AFTER HE STARTED LOADING THE CAR. THE EMPLOYEE WAS COUNSELED AND RECEIVED DISPLINARY ACTIONS FOR NOT FOLLOWING THE ESTABLISHED LOADING PROCEDURES FOR TANK CARS.

column168: ON 07/18/2013 AT 0936 HRS CDT, I WAS ADVISED OF TANK CAR LEAKING PRODUCT AND SMELL FROM RAILCAR FURX 123302 ON TRACK #9 AT THE INDIANA HARBOR BELT (IHB) RAILROAD, BURNHAM YARD, IN BURNHAM (CHICAGO) ILLINOIS.    I SUBSEQUENTLY PROCEEDED TO BURNHAM YARD AND MET WITH TRAINMASTER, WHO ADVISED ME IN THE SUMMARY THAT DURING GROUND INSPECTION OF THE CAR, TRAIN CREW NOTED SMELL AND SOME LEAKAGE ON MANWAY. TRAINMASTER ADVISED THAT HE TOOK A LOOK AT MANWAY AND THOUGHT PART OF THE MANWAY GASKET WAS MISSING. I PROCEEDED TO INSPECT CAR AND NOTED MANWAY SEALED WITH #JJ KELLER 36711. INSPECTION OF GASKET REVEALED, THAT A COMPLETE SEAL WAS NOT EVIDENT AS EVIDENCED BY NOT BEING COMPLETELY VISIBLE ON CIRCUMFERENCE BETWEEN MANWAY COVER AND HOUSING. SEAL WAS REMOVED BY SUNPRO SERVICES WHO I CONTACTED FOR GASKET REPLACEMENT. THE GASKET THAT WAS REMOVED WAS BADLY WORN, TORN, AND DEGRADED. (PHOTOS #5&6) SUNPRO SERVICES REPLACED GASKET IN ACCORDANCE WITH SPEC PROVIDED BY "TOTAL PETROCHEMICALS AND REFINING USA". MANWAY WAS SUBSEQUENTLY SEALED WITH # JJ KELLER 36708 WAS REMOVED TO INSPECCT VALVES AND NO EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED AND VALVE BOX WAS RELEASED WITH # ONESEAL 24015763. FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE CAR, REVEALED LEAKAGE RESIDUE WAS EVIDENT ON THE RIGHT CENTER OF CAR MANWAY (PHOTO #2) CONSISTENT WHERE THE GASKET WAS NOT VISIBLE. CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.
column169: SINCE THIS MANWAY ON THIS RAILCAR WS UNDER SEAL, IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN OBVIOUS THAT THE MANWAY GASKET, WAS TORN, WORN AND DEGRADED AFTER LOADING THE CAR AND PRIOR TO SEALING THE MANWAY AND OFFERING IT IN TRANSPORTATION.    BEST PRACTICES AND REVIEW OF PROCEDURES BEFORE RELEASING RAILCARS OFFERED IN TRANSPORTATION FOR ANY DEFECTS SHOULD BE INITIATED AS SOON AS POSSIBLE TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: DRIVER APPLIED HIS BRAKES TOO HARD CAUSING HIS LOAD TO SHIFT FORWARD RESULTING IN A LOAD SHIFT. THE FORCE OF ALL 16 TOTES BEING MOVED FORWARD APPLIED PRESSURE TO THE TWO 330 GALLON TOTES IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. AS A RESULT OF THE SEVERE PRESSURE ONE TOTE WS PUNCTURED WHICH ALLOWED AN ESTIMATED 150 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE SECOND TOTE ONLY RECEIVED STRUCTURAL DAMAGED WHICH CAUSED A PIN HOLE LEAK. THE RELEASED PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WHICH THEN MIGRATED TO THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER WHERE IT RAN OUT AND ONTO THE GROUND (SOIL). QUICK ACTION BY THE MOAB FIRE DEPARTMENT AIDED IN THE CONTAINMENT OF THE RELEASED PRODUCT. FOUR LIDDY POOLS WERE UTILIZED FOR THE CONTAINMENT OF THE RELEASED PRODUCT.    A LOCAL ENVIROMENTAL COMPANY HAD BEEN DISPACHED TO THE SITE FOR CLEANUP. THE TWO LEAKING TOTES WERE TRANSFERRED TO NEW TOTES TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE. AN ADDITIONAL 3 MORE TOTES WERE ALSO TRANSFERRED FOR PRECAUTIONARY REASONS. THE RELEASED PRODUCT IN THE KIDDY POOLS HAD ALSO BEEN TRANSFERRED INTO RECEIVING TOTES FOR CONTAINMENT.    THE IMPACTED SOIL HAD BEEN EXCAVATED TO REMOVE ALL TRACES OF PRODUCT FROM THE SITE AND THE SOIL. THE TOTES OF PRODUCT (16) WERE ALL LOADED BACK ONTO THE TRUCK FOR DELIVERY. THE IMPACTED SOIL HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE SITE FOR DISPOSAL AT AN APPROVED DISPOSAL FACILITY.
column169: CONTINUE DRIVER TRAINING, ADDITIONAL TRAINING REGARDING PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING AS WELL AS DRIVER AWARENESS TRAINING TO PREVENT SUDDEN STOPS OR HARD BRAKING.

column168: After arrival on a BNSF intermodal train, intermodal trailer FXFZ 973347 was reported leaking an unknown substance that was hardening. FXFZ 973347 was carefully removed from its rail flatcar and taken to the facility's containment area. Contract responders inspecting FXFZ 973347 reported insufficient blocking and bracing of the lading within FXFZ 973347 allowed load shifting during transit. Several top stacked crates fell onto nearby lading below. One 5 gallon steel pail was partially crushed and punctured by fallen lading. Responders overpacked this damaged pail. The hardened spillage was removed from the floor of FXFZ 973347. Afterwards, all lading was returned inside FXFZ 973347 properly blocked and braced for continued transportation.
column169: Ensure shipper's hazardous material LTL shipments are properly blocked and braced to avoid lading damages during transportation.

column168: On July 3, 2013, an R&L Carriers terminal experienced a release of Washoff 140 product from a 55-galllon drum due to puncture by forklift. Environmental Services Inc was dispatched to the site for cleanup activities. Absorbents were applied to the impacted dock and the damaged drum was placed into an over pack drum. All contaminated material was containerized and staged onsite for reclamation by the shipper.

A van trailer loaded with multiple shipments of hazardous waste was about to be transported to the intended waste disposal facility when, during a routine pre-trip inspection, the driver noticed a wet area underneath the trailer.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  The trailer floor was wet underneath a pallet on which 2 of 4 drums were found to have pinhole leaks.  The drums were overpacked into suitable salvage containers and the absorbent material used to clean up the spill on the ground and the trailer floor was also placed into the salvage drums.  The trailer then proceeded to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The drums were picked up on 7-23 and showed no signs of leaking.  They remained on that trailer and there were no signs of leaking during regular yard checks each day.  The drums were old and showed signs of corrosion.  The customer was notified to use better care when choosing old drums for loading for transport.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Residue tank car DGCX 1178 was reported emanating an odor in the railyard. DGCX 1178 was cordoned off in the railyard.  BNSF hazardous material responders immediately inspected DGCX 1178 and reported finding the B-end liquid valve partially open with its closure plug only hand tight. The responders closed the B-end liquid valve and the commodity odor dissipated. The loose closure plug was then removed and Teflon tape was applied to its threaded areas, reinserted into its orifice and properly tool tightened. No other securement issues were noted. Response was concluded by 0730 hrs. CDT, 7/31/2013 after no further residue commodity vapors/odors were detectable.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Upon inspection, the car was found to be leaking from the liquid valve. The packing gland nut was off and the packing was out. This caused approximately fifteen gallons of product to release from the car. The packing was reinstalled and the packing gland nut was reapplied and made wrench tight. The leak was stopped and the car was released to destination.

column168: NICK SWISHER NOTIFIED ME AT 4:30 AM THAT THERE WAS A LEAKING PACKAGE IN TRAILER NUMBER 337834. I DONNED MY PPE, DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET TO RESPOND TO THE SOIL. THE UNLOADER EXITED THE TRAILER AND I IDENTIFIED THAT THE PACKAGE WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (CORROSIVE). I TESTED THE PH OF THE PACKAGE AND THEN MOVED THE PACKAGE TO THE DMP AREA. SHORTLY THEREAFTER I NOTICED THAT THERE WERE VISIBLE FUMES COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE PACKAGE. AT THIS POINT I CALLED MY MANAGER AND INFORMED HIM THAT I NEEDED TO CONTACT PLANT ENGINEERING SO AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER COULD BE DISPTACHED. I CORDONED OFF THE AREA AND ISOLATED THE PACKAGE FROM THE EMPLOYEES. THEN I CALLED SPILL COORDINATOR ROB SHEDDEN AND INFORMED HIM OF THE ISSUE. ALSO CALLED CHSP SUPERVISOR JANA POLITSCH. ROB CONTACTED ME AND SAID THAT THE OUTSIDE RESPONDER WOULD BE ON SITE BY 09:00 AM. THEY ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 08:50 AM. I REVIEWED THE LOCATION OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PACKAGE WITH THE OUTSIDE RESPONDER AS WELL AS THE SPILL IN THE TRAILER.
column169: SPILL COORDINATOR ROB SHEDDEN CONTACTED THE ORIGIN SITE (CACH NIGHT SORT) TO REVIEW SPILL WITH THE MANAGEMENT TEAM.

column168: On July 25, 2013, a Veolia employee was using an electric pallet jack to move a 275 gal tote (IBC) from one trailer to another.  While moving the tote into the trailer, the employee accidentally steered the tote into a metal clamping mechanism that's attached to the back side wall entry way of the trailer.  The metal clamp punctured the side wall of the tote spilling an estimated 20 gallons of material.    The puncture in the tote was located in the lower side of the tote.  The release lasted approximately two hours.  Fifteen minutes after the tote was punctured it was placed on top of a poly containment system which contained the remaining material that leaked from the tote.    The material that leaked was cleaned up and sent to a proper waste disposal facility.  The material in the poly containment system was transferred into a new tote for disposal.  The punctured tote was sent to a proper waste disposal facility.
column169: Veolia employees at Schenectady, NY were trained to bungee the metal clamp against the side wall of the trailer.  This will eliminate the clamp from protruding outward and being able to puncture any containers. The Veolia employee involved in the incident was given electric pallet jack re-training.

While stopped at a transfer facility to transfer the materials to a second transporter, the Veolia ES Technical Solutions driver noticed an acidic odor in the cargo compartment of his truck when opening the rear door.  The Veolia driver donned a respirator and protective clothing and entered the truck to determine the source of the odor.  The Veolia driver observed an 85 gallon plastic drum that was emitting red vapors from the edges of the screw top lid.  The outer drum contained 20x1 gallon(half full) containers of corrosive liquids.  Approximately 3 of the 1 gallon inner containers were found to be damaged.  The Veolia driver enacted the Veolia emergency response plan.  A response team was dispatched to the site and using level B personal protective equipment, entered the truck and stabilized the salvage drum using dry inorganic absorbent.  The response team noted that there was also some cardboard and other material in the outer drum that was likely the source of the reaction with the corrosive materials.  The drum was monitored for several hours to ensure that no further reaction occurred. No liquid or solid material was released from the contaienr during the incident.  The container was then transported by Veolia to the Veolia Port Arthur incineration facility for treatment and disposal.
column169: The Veolia driver and Veolia sales and customer service had knowledge that this drum contained material that was damaged and had a history of problems at the shippers facility.  The material should have been handled as a special project by Veolias field service team and properly inspected and re-packed into proper contaienrs for shipment and disposal.

column168: Our driver was loaded at Eastman Chemical Plant where their plant operators perform all preloading inspection and loading activities, our driver is prohibited from examining the unit inside the Eastman Plantsite.  The driver departed the plant and drove to the first safe-haven approximately 2 miles from the plant to perform his post-loading inspection.  He discovered the material draining from the crash box and made the appropriate notifications.  The leak was cleaned up by the Eastman Chemical internal response team, upon clean-up they discovered the trailer dome lid gasket was missing.  The gasket was replaced, they resealed the trailer and released our unit.
column169: Eastman Chemical conducts all their own inspections upon loading, our driver followed proper procedure during this incident.

column168: It was reported that during the transfer of crude oil from a storage tank to a cargo tank, the driver realized that the sample had too much water.  Instead of disconnecting and offloading the bad oil into a different tank, the driver attempted to blow it back into the storage tank he was loading from. As a result, the tank's overflow hatch opened up and released approximately 100 gallons of crude oil into the containment area.  We called ERTS (our enviromental vendor) to send out an emergency response crew to clean up the spill.
column169: The driver did not follow proper procedure and is no longer with our company.

column168: Driver was transferring product from our cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  The storage tank was not transparent and the driver was not aware if it had a sight glass. The customer told the driver there was plenty of room in the tank to handle all of the product.  When driver saw product come out of the overflow of the storage tank, he immediately stopped the transfer.  The spill went in to a containment area and the customer handled cleanup.  they put the product remaining in the cargo tank, into a tote.
column169: The amount in the tank should have been verified before the unload to determine if there was enough room.

column168: While the driver was transferring product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank, product started to leak from the product transfer pump on his tractor.  he immediately stopped the transfer.  About 1 qt leaked out and the driver was able to absorb it with spill pads.  Delivery was completed with a different pump.
column169: The pump was brought it for maintenance and 2 new discharge line gaskets were installed.  Leaks of this type are not normal so no suggestions for preventing other ocurrences.

column168: On 0729/2013 at 1328 personnel with CSX Intermodal Charlotte Terminal discovered  CSXU631315, a loaded container of Potassium Nitrate in 50lbbags leaked approx 5 lbs solidified powder on bottom of container and small spots on asphalt pavement. The container was isolated and NRC rept#1055426 and NC EMA report# n/a were notified. The shipper, CSXI Trucking representatives Tana Lucas 904-633-1208 was notified by CSXI Cust Svc. Hepaco, CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found three pallets of 50lb plastic bags leaked 5lbs product due to bags water-soaked and damged. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel over-packed damaged bags which secured the leak, deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the material. All lading put back in original freight container with proper load/block/brace and released to the shipper.    This incident did not require a special switching move.   This incident did not require a Form 7.1.

column168: On July 29, 2013, at 0517, personnel in the CSXT Avon Yard discovered UTLX130308, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. Summit Contracting, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the gasket on the fill hole cover was not properly aligned.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Chad Blake at 412-777-7475.  Contractor personnel installed a new gasket that was provided by Mr. Chad Blake and decontaminated the outside of the car.  The leak was secured and the car released for transport. Tank car SHPX 207027 was reported leaking commodity from its bottom sump area in the railyard. SHPX 207027 was cordoned off at its location in the railyard. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders were able to insert a sealing plug in the half inch diameter corrosion hole at the sump to stop the commodity release. The remaining commodity within SHPX 207027 was transloaded into other suitable tank cars that were available in the railyard with the final transload accomplished without further incident into a tank truck. Observed concentrated ground spillage was excavated with the entire spill area treated with a lime covering. Excavated soils were placed into disposable poly drums along with contaminated PPE and all drums earmarked for appropriate disposal.

column168: THE DRUM WAS LOADED DIRECTLY ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WITHOUT BEING SECURED. WHILE REMOVING THE SHIPMENT DIRECTLY BEHIND THE SKID THIS SHIPMENT SHOULD HAVE BEEN ON, THE SKID PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF THE PLASTIC DRUM. THE DRUM WAS TILTED ON ITS SIDE TO LIMIT THE AMOUNT OF CHEMICAL THAT RELEASED. THE HOLE IN THE DRUM WAS NO LARGER THAN TWO INCHES ACROSS.
column169: THE SHIPMENT SHOULD HAVE BEEN LOADED ON THE SKID AND STRAPPED TO THE WALL OF THE TRAILER. CARDBOARD DAMAGE SHOULD HAVE BEEN USED UNDER THE SKID TO PROVIDE SAME CUSHION AND TO HELP ABSORB ANY POTENTIAL SPILL.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While entering parking lot at Ace Hardware in Cary, North Carolina, it appears the freight shifted and punctured one (1) 300-gallon tote of caustic soda 50%, being shipped as sodium hydroxide solution. As a result, approximately 250 gallons of free product released to the trailer floor and asphalt parking lot. Gary Fire Department responded to assess the site, and proceeded to wash the parking lot with excessive amounts of water. As a result, free product and water affected the asphalt parking lot entrance, around to back of store, and impacted outside pallets and debris being held outside the hardware store. Environmental Restoration and Hepaco were dispatched to perform the cleanup. Upon arrival on site, absorbent material was applied to the affected area, in an effort to contain. Due to the large area of impact, as a result of the fire department water placement, a vacuum truck was dispatched to recover free liquids from the lot. Environmental Restoration and Hepaco personnel proceeded to recover free product and wash waters from the parking lot, while neutralizing the caustic material. Once the parking lot was secure, Hepaco, Inc. proceeded to offload trailer, clean impacted trailer floor and surrounding areas, and containerize remaining free product. Freight was loaded onto a recovery trailer provided by Wilson Trucking Corporation, to be sent on to its destination. Following a rain event in the area, Hepaco returned to the site, collected residual product, and site was deemed for closure. Disposal was coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were on injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Wilson Trucking Corporation will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: On July 27, 2013, 0200 hours, Kirk Higbie, Director of Safety & Environmental, Terminal Railroad Association, 8934 Manchester Street, Houston, Texas 77012-2149, contacted M&M Protection and advised that there was a rail car at the Pasadena Yard that was leaking out of the dome lid and requested that we respond. The car number UTLX 668107, load of Xylene. M&M Protection, LLC responded with personnel and equipment necessary to open the rail cars covers and determine the source of the leaks. Rail car was located at the PTRA Pasadena yard. M&M personnel arrived on site to notice that there was an individual on top of the rail car working on the dome. When M&M personnel asked who the person was, it was stated that it was a repairman from Vopak named Lonnie Dunlap. The rail car was found to have a dome gasket that was bent and folded causing the product to leak from the dome. M&M Protection supplied one dome lid gasket to the Vopak repairman. The Vopak repairman placed a new gasket on the dome, closed and tightened the lid and placed a new seal on the dome.
column169: VOPAK responded to the scene to investigate and secure the car. They will be reviewing the incident to prevent future occurences.

column168: (A) On 07/25/2013, at 0100, personnel in the CSXT Tampa Port discovered BDUX 301553, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., Denatured Alcohol, derailed, leaning and  leaking from manway and the liquid line valve bolted flange. The car was isolated and the shipper, Valero Marketing and Supply Company, local fire department and police, state and federal agencies were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report # 2013-0725-00011). CSX personnel, SWS, and Arcadis, CSXT emergency response contractors, were dispatched to the scene and found the car derailed, leaning and leaking from the manway and the liquid line valve bolted flange. The issues were identified, all of the manway bolts were less than tool tight and three out of four of the liquid line valve bolted flange bolts were less than tool tight. Corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Susan Schaffer 210-262-1551. Contractor personnel secured the manway bolts, secured the liquid line valve flange, re-railed the car  and  cleaned up the spilled material. CSX personnel and United States Environmental Services USES, a  CSXT emergency response contractor, were dispatched to the scene and found the Salco style PRV inspection cap damaged and the rupture was activated and the surge protection device was broken off and missing . column168: CN transportation department employee noted an odor coming from tank car RACX 51393 (Load: Styrene Monomer Stabilized. UN2055) while passing on an adjacent track at the CN Markham Yard, Markham, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting seals in tact. Liquid was noted coming from the manway, two swing bolts on the manway were found less than tool tight allowing product to escape. Car was found to have no outage and was overloaded by volume. The load was reduced to proper level. Manway gasket was replaced and properly secured. Liquid valve was found to be leaking on the completion of the load reduction. Valve was replaced, prepared for transportation and new seals applied. Tank car was released for movement.

column168: Clean Harbors chemists were intransit to the Clean Harbors TSDF in Laurel MD and noticed the drum was off-gassing. Elkton Fire arrived along with the Maryland MDE, NRC and a Clean Harbors response team. The drum was monitored constantly and it was decided by all parties to fill drum with water which stopped the reaction and off gassing. column168: DOWX 71071, loaded tank car, was involved in a derailment in La Grande, OR. Investigation of the derailed cars found this car to be releasing product from the bottom outlet valve mounting flange. All 8 bolts to the flange were tool tight. The car was trans-loaded to highway vehicles and is to be home shopped for repair.      Further investigation revealed a deteriorated gasket. These results indicate the release was present prior to the derailment occurring and that the derailment was not the cause of the release. There was no physical damage to any of the valves.
column169: Continue dilgence in proper securement or tank fiitings and valves. Check gaskets during every loading and unloading procedure.

column168: After arrival of top stacked intermodal container NYKU 591407 (destined for export) on a BNSF intermodal train, it was observed leaking an unknown liquid on containers below it and also on its rail flatcar it was riding upon. NYKU 591407 was carefully removed from the rail car and taken to the facility's containment area. Contract responders cleaned the spillage from all impacted container and rail equipment. Another contractor investigated the leak source within NYKU 591407. Responders found one 55 gallon steel drum with a small crack located within a dented area at its bottom rolling hoop. Responders concluded that the dent and subsequent crack were incurred during drum handling and/or loading at origin prior to rail transportation. The crack was patched, placed in an over-pack drum, secured and properly labeled. Container floor spillage was washed and cleaned. Afterwards, all lading was returned within NYKU 591407 properly blocked and braced for continued transportation.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: WHILE CONDUCTING THE BREAKDOWN THE ULD ON WHICH THE DGR DRUMS WERE LOADED, ONE DRUM FELL OFF OF THE FORKLIFT BLADES AND ENDED UP UPSIDE DOWN. column168: Air Liquide Driver Keith Boddy was traveling in the right lane eastbound on I-24 near exit 161. He changed lanes to the left lane to pass a slower moving truck (Transfreight) in the right lane as as he was 3/4 completed with the pass, the Transfreight Driver proceeded to move his truck into the left lane, striking the Air Liquide transport on the passenger side and forcing him off the road into the highway median on his left and causing the transport to rollover. The inner vessel of the trailer was intact, however gaseous nitrogen needed to be vented out of the road relief valve to reduce the weight of the transport so the wrecker (Glenn's Wrecker Service)could bring the transport upright and tow from the scene. The AL driver was transported to Memorial Hospital in Chattanooga via ambulance to be evaluated and he received minor injuries from the accident. Trooper Terrence Gann of the TN Highway patrol and Steve Lamb from the Marion County EMA were on the scene to manage the incident.
column169: The vehicle accident / rollover was caused by the Transfreight Driver and he was cited for failure to maintain lane and due care.    The incident was shared with all Air Liquide Industrial professional drivers and defensive driving techniques and fatigue management techniques were discussed to help prevent a similar type of accident from happening in the future.

column168: DSR was transporting a skid from pro# 513835523 down the dock to load onto a outbound trailer. As he put the skid onto the trailer, a leak was noticed. Upon further review, it was noticed that a small piece of wood was wedged into the side of one of the drums. When DSR placed the skid down into the loading door, the small piece of wood worked itself out of the side of the drum thus causing the leak. It was discovered soon enough that only about 5 to 8 ounces leaked out of the drum. Photos were taken of the piece of wood and the side of the drum.  Cleaned up in house.

column168: Investigation of the incident determined that employee error was the likely cause of the spill. The driver of the truck had stopped his vehicle on the county road while waiting in line to enter the facility. He took this as an opportunity to loosen the tarp of the roll-off container to expedite opening the tarp once he arrived at the facility sample rack. When he loosened the tarp, the roll-off container began to leak from the bottom seal of the tail-gate. It has not been determined why loosening the tarp would cause or if it could cause such a leak to occur. The driver stated that he made no other adjustments to any other closures of the container. The spill was along a length of the county road approximately 200 feet south of entrance to Heritage Environmental Services, LLC and from the facility entrance to the facility scale. Heritage believes there were no actual or potential hazards to the environment or the human health outside the facility. This determination is based on a review of the waste analysis and samples collected following clean up actions.
column169: The driver has been instructed to not make any unwarranted adjustments to containers and closures during transport, especially outside of designated loading and unloading areas or sampling areas.

column168: On July 24, 2013, the carrier (Seaboard Marine) was advised by PriceSmart that undeclared hazardous materials were stowed inside container TCKU975088-2 (UN1950 AEROSOLS). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) received notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded.  Upon receiving notice from the shipper we immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and subsequently released for transportation

column168: Gasoline Product Hose ruptured during off-loading to customer storage tank. The delivery was a pump fed offload and there was minimal pressure, the hose emptied its contents on to the ground before the driver was able to shut the loading valve. The estimated duration of the release was 15-20 seconds and size of the hose rupture was approximately 2 inches in diameter. Mitigating efforts were immediately taken the driver shut down the flow of product within 20 seconds and immediately placed speedy dry absorbent and pads down at the site to prevent the spread of the product. In addition, fueling at the gas station was suspended until the fire department and clean up contractor arrived on-site.
column169: Investigate the potential to change the delivery hose from a 3" diameter 65 PSI hose to a high pressure 150 PSI delivery hose. Conduct annual hose pressure test at 1.5 times the working pressure. Investigate the design of the hose connection at the delivery site to reduce potential strain on hose.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 4:45PM, ON JULY 17, 2013, THE AIRGAS USA, LLC DRIVER WAS FINISHING HIS SHIFT AFTER MAKING DELIVERIES IN THE NORTHEAST PHILADELPHIA AREA WHEN HE COLLIDED WITH THE BACK OF A SLOW MOVING STREET SWEEPER. THE DRIVER WAS ON HIS WAY BACK TO THE BELLMAWR, NJ APM PLANT OPERATING A COMPANY-OWN 2009 GMC CAB OVER, 6 WHEEL BOX TRUCK (PURLTAN PLUS). THE TRUCK WAS TRANSPORTING A 210 GALLON TANK OF LIQUID OXYGEN AND NUMEROUS EA OXYGEN CYLINDERS. AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT, 1 (1) ONE INCH LINE COMING OFF THE BOTTOM OF THE 210 GALLON TANK WAS PUNCTURE RELEASING LESS THAN 1 GALLON OF GASEOUS OXYGEN INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. LOCAL RESPONDERS WERE ABLE TO STOP AND SECURE THE LEAK. THE VEHICLE REMAINED SECURED AT THE ACCIDENT SCENE UNTIL AIRGAS USA, LLC EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL ARRIVED TO INSPECT THE PORTABLE TANK TO ENSURE THE VEHICLE WAS SAFE FOR REMOVAL FROMTHE ACCIDENT SCENE. THE VEHICLE CONTAINING THE PORTABLE TANK WAS REMOVED TO A SALVAGE YARD WITH NO FURTHER MATERIAL RELEASE. BOTH THE DRIVER OF THE AIRGAS USA, LLC AND THE DRIVER OF THE STREET SWEEPER WERE TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL, TREATED, AND RELEASED THE SAME DAY.

column168: EMI JOB #34196: MR. TIRSO BELTRAIN OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT (EMI) RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. DON LONSDALE OF SMITH SYSTEMS TRANSPORTATION, INC. (SST). MR. LONSDALE REPORTED THAT AN SST DRIVER (MR. STEVE SCHROEDER) HAD REPORTED THAT HE HAD DISCOVERED A LIQUID MATERIAL LEAKING FROM A CONTAINER(S) THAT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED ON A TRAILER (FLATBET). MR. LONSDALE INFORMED MR. BELTRAN THAT ELECTRICAL TRANSFORMSERS, PCB WASTE IN DRUMS, AND OTHER PCB ITEMS WERE BEING TRANSPORTED. THE TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT WAS LOCATED IN THE PARKING LOT OF SAPP BROTHERS TRUCK STOP LOCATED AT 380 ODESSA ROAD IN ELM CREEK, NEBRASKA. MR. LONSDALE REQUESTED THAT EMI COORDINATE A RESPONSE TO THE RELEASE. MR. BELTRAN CONTACTED MR. SCHROEDER FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION. MR. SCHROEDER STATED THAT A TRANSFORMER OR TRANSFORMERS WERE BELIEVED TO BE LEAKING. THE ITEMS WERE LOCATED IN A CONTAINMENT AREA ON THE TRAILER. SOME OF THE LIQUID HAD SPILLED OUT OF THE CONTAINMENT AND IMPACTED THE PARKING LOT (SOIL). NO STORM DRAINS OR NAVIGABLE WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED. MR. SCHROEDER HAS DEPLOYED ABSORBENT MATERIALS TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE. MR. BELTRAN CONTACTED HAZ-MAT RESPONSE, INC. (HMR), AN EMI APPROVED ENVIRONMENTAL SUBCONTRACTOR. MR. BELTRAN SPOKE WITH MR. JOSH SUMMERS AND REQUESTED THAT HMRI RESPOND TO THE RELEASE ON BEHALF OF EMI. MR. SUMMERS STATED THAT HE WOULD ASSEMBLE A RESPONSE TEM AND EQUIPMENT AND MOBILIZE TO THE SITE. HMRI ARRIVED ON SITE AND LOCATED THE UNIT. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE LIQUID HAD IMPACTED THE SOIL ON BOTH SIDES OF THE TRAILER. THE IMPACTED AREA WAS APPROXIMATELY 53 FEET LONG AND 12 FEET IN WIDTH. MR. SAM SMITH (SST) ALSO ARRIVED ONSITE. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, IT WAS OBSERVED THAT A SMALL INSULATOR LOCATED NEAR THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE TRANSFORMERS HAD BROKEN, CAUSING THE RELEASE. THE TRANSFORMER HAD BEEN SECURED WITH STRAPS BUT HAD SHIFTED AND STRUCK ANOTHER TRANSFORMER CAUSING THE SMALL INSULATOR TO BREAK. APPROXIMATELY 70 TO 80 GALLONS OF LIQUID (68PPM) HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE TRANSFORMER (S/N 67B9560). HMRI PERSONNEL THEN DRAINED THE REMAINING LIQUID (APPROXIMATELY 55-GALLONS) INTO A DRUM. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT THE LIQUID HAD ALSO BREACHED THE CONTAINMENT AREA AND IMPACTED THE WOOD DECKING OF THE TRAILER FLOOR. AFTER A DISCUSSION BETWEEN MR. SMITH AND MR. SUMMERS, IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE LIQUID FROM THE REMAINING TWO TRANSFORMERS (NOT LEAKING AT THAT TIME) WOULD BE TRANSFERRED TO DRUMS. ALL CONTAINERS ON THE TRAILER WOULD THEN BE LOADED INTO ROLL-OFF BOXES WITH ABSORBENTS TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER RELEASES WHILE IN TRANSPORT. SST PROVIDED TWO (2) ROLL-OFF BOXES AND HMRI PROVIDE ANOTHER TWO (2) ROLL-OFF BOXES FOR THE ITEMS TO BE TRANSPORTED TO US ECOLOGY (DESIGNATED DISPOSAL FACILITY) IN GRAND VIEW, IDAHO. NEW MANIFESTS WOULD BE FILLED OUT FOR EACH LOAD. ONCE THE CARGO WAS REMOVED FROM THE IMPACTED TRAILER, THE WOOD DECKING WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND PLACED INTO A SEPARATE ROLL-OFF BOX PROVIDED BY HMRI. THE TRAILER FRAME WAS THEN WIPED DOWN TO REMOVE ALL F

The subject fire commenced on July 29, 2013 at approximately 10:35 in the storage yard at the Blue Rhino production facility in Tavares, Florida.  This facility is a regional center for the cleaning, painting, refurbishing (as needed) and refilling of 20 lb. tanks with propane.  As a part of the the usual production activities, filled tanks ready for commercial distribution are placed in the storage yard, on pallets awaiting transportation to local distributors.       During the second shift on July 29, 4 workers went to the back of the storage yard to check tanks 16 pallets of paint damaged tanks.  Approximately 10-15 minutes later, the fire started.  Workers located approximately 100 yards away, saw the fire in the very back of the storage yard, in the general area that the 4 workers should have been working.      The fire spread relatively quickly and some of the filled 20 lb. tanks on site were propelled into the air, with some landing off site (there were approximately 79.696 tanks on the premises, of which approximately 38,052 were filled).  Fire Department personnel were able to extinguish the fire in the morning hours of July 30.  The fire damaged or destroyed the vast majority of the 20 lb tanks in the storage yard, along with several tractors, trailers and two forklifts.  The 3 bulk storage tanks for propane on site and the two production building were not involved in the fire, and sustained minor damage.
column169: The incident is still currently under investigation.

column168: SOME ONE CALLED THE WATERTOWN PD COMPLAIN OF A AMMONIA SMELL. THE SMELL WAS ISOLATED TO A CHS OWNED TRAILER LOCATED IN AN OWNER/OPERATOR OWNED FACILITY. THE VESSEL CONTAINED ONLY RESIDUE WHEN PARKED IT WAS PARKED BY THE O/O. THE TRAILER WAS TOWED OUT OF TOWN BY THE CODINGTON COUNTY, SC SHERIFF AND CHS WAS ALLOWED TO TOW THE TRAILER DOWN TO OUR SIOUX FALLS FOR REPAIRE. UPON INSPECTION BY CHS MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL AT OUR SIOUX FALLS FACILITY THEY DETERMINED THAT THE 8 O'CLOCK BOLT ON THE REAR MANWAY WAS LOOSE AND ALLOWED FOR PRODUCT TO SLOWLY LEAK OUT OF THE VESSEL.
column169: THE MANWAY WAS REMOVED AND A NEW GASKET INSTALLED ON THE TRAILER. ALL AMMONIA TRAILERS THAT HAD THE MANWAY WORKED ON SINCE NOV. 2012 WERE REMOVED FROM SERVICE TO HAVE THEIR MANWAY BOLTS EXAMINED AND TIGHTENED IF NEEDED.

column168: GLNX 23444 was found to be leaking from the top of the car in the El Dorado, AR yard.  The car was inspected and found to have product in the housing as well as the side of the car.  No active leak was observed.  The car was wiped clean and re-inspected the following day and found to have a small amount of product on the side of the car with the housing clean.  The pressure plate bolts were found to be 1/2 to 3/4 turn loose.  The car was placed in hold status until bubble tested.  Bubble test was performed and a bad Vacuum relief valve was found and replaced, along with a new manway gasket and bottom outlet gasket.  Car was released back into transportation upon final bubble test.

column168: Driver pulled up to the #2 unload station. He observed that the environmental containment bucket was full so he hooked up his hose to the facility and removed crude from the containment bucket through the 1" piping. Afterwards the driver was ready to unload his crude into the facility and failed to reverse his pump thinking he had done so already. The driver then left his truck (in load operation) to go fill out his paperwork and due to heavy rain the log in the mailbox was soaked and unuseable. Driver went inside the location's office to retreive another log. When he returned to his truck (according to driver 2-3 minutes after walking away) approximately 10 bbls. of crude had overloaded out of his truck onto the ground below.     Along with improper unloading procedure a check valve in place at the facility failed causing crude to be unloaded from the tank battery and loaded onto the truck.     Overfill caused crude to be released onto location covering an area of approximately 40x20 yards with 40% coverage.  Heavy rains prior and during incident carried spilled crude  off of location into neighboring land to the Southwest. Neighboring land received crude carried by rainwater and covered a downhill slope leading up to the Big Spring facility as well as 1270ft. into a waterway leading out towards Beals Creek. Spill was contained to the waterway and did not reach Beals Creek (approximately 500 ft. further downstream).
column169: Berm walls will be added to Southwest edge of location to help prevent potential future releases from leaving the facility into neighboring land.    All check valves/ball valves will be replaced on the central battery facility to help prevent future failure.    Will review this incident with all HST employees and contractors as lessons learned.

Driver felt vechile trailer to begin to swerve left & right. Driver attemped to maintain control of vehicle by holding steering wheel straight. Driver applied breaks just as driver was approaching the I-5 over-cross. Driver looked into right rear view mirrow and observed trailer swerving to the right , towards asphalt shoulder. Driver related vehicle trailer tilted to the right and subsequiently overturned onto it's right side, colliding with the concrete roadway. Vehicle slid forward, on it's right side, and slid under the I-5 overcross.

column168: THE CARGO TANK INVOLVED HAD BEEN IN A TRAILER REPAIR FACILITY IN WEST MEMPHIS, AR FOR REPAIR OF THE EXTERNAL VALVE. THE MECHANIC REPAIRING THE VALVE FAILED TO USE THE PROPER BOLTS WHEN RE-ASSEMBLING THE VALVE. THE BOLTS INSTALLED WERE TOO SHORT. THE VEHICLE WAS PICKED UP FROM THE BUSINESS, LOADED WITH MOLTEN SULFUR AND WAS HEADED TO IT'S DESTINATION WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED AT A STOP SIGN, THE VALVE WAS LEAKING MOLTEN SULFUR. HE ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE VALVE, BUT THE SHORT BOLTS THAT WERE IMPROPERLY INSTALLED FAILED, AND SULFUR BEGAN FLOWING FROM THE VALVE. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND THEY BEGAN POURING WATER ON THE VALVE TO FREEZE THE MOLTEN SULFUR INTO A SOLID STATE. US ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED FOR CLEANUP. THE BUSINESS THAT REPAIRED THE VALVE TOOK FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE DAMAGE AND CLEANUP. LESS THAN A GALLON GOT INTO A SEWER DRAIN, AND WAS ALSO CLEANED UP BY THE CONTRACTOR.
column169: IN THE FUTURE, WHEN REMOVING AND REPLACING EXTERNAL VALVES, MAKE SURE THE PROPER LENGTH BOLTS ARE USED.

column168: THE RELEASE OCCURRED DURING THE LOADING OF A TANKER TRUCK WITH SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE. THE 4" FLEXIBLE HOSE STRETCHING FROM THE PLANT FIXED LOADING HEADER TO THE 10" OPEN DOME HATCH ON THE TANKER SHIFTED DURING LOADING RESULTING IN APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF 12.5% SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANKER WITH A PORTION GOING TO CONTAINMENT AND SOME FLOWING OVER AN ENGINEERED SURFACE TO THE NEAREST STORM SEWER APPROXIMATELY 125 FEET.
column169: WHEN THE RELEASE WAS FIRST OBSERVED THE TANKER DRIVER PULLED FORWARD, SO THE RELEASE MATERIAL WOULD DRAIN TO THE CONTAINED AREA. RESPONDING PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY COVERED THE STORM DRAIN AND BEGAN NEUTRALIZING THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE. WATER WAS USED TO FLUSH THE MATERIAL BACK INTO THE CONTAINED AREA AND AWAY FROM THE STORM DRAIN.    DESIGN MODIFICATIONS OF THE LOADING HOSE ARE BEING EVALUATED TO ENSURE THAT ONCE PLACED, THE HOSE WILL NOT SHIFT DURING LOADING.

column168: On July 17, 2013, at 2005, personnel on the MSE train crew working in Big Point Sidding discovered ECUX 569055, a loaded tank car of Butadiene, leaking from dome area. The car was isolated and the National response center and Exxon Mobil Chemical were notified.  (Chemtrec 2013071700328). United States Environmental Services, a Exxon Mobil emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found Leaking SRV. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper.  Contractor U.S.E.S put a midland kit on the car to move for transloading. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move which was granted by the FRA. The car was safely transloaded, purged, re stenciled and shopped for corrective action.

column169: WHEN WE BROUGHT UNIT BACK AND SENT TO HAVE VALVE FIXED OR REPLACED I WAS INFORMED THAT SOMETHING WAS CARRIED IN THE TANKER THAT HAD ATTACKED THE INTERNAL LINER AND VALVE ASSEMBLY AND COMPROMISED THE INTEGRITY OF THE UNIT. SO IT COULD NOT BE USED AS A HAZMAT SPEC TANKER AGAIN AND HAS BEEN REMOVED FROM SERVICE.    I HAD LEASED THE UNIT TO ANOTHER HAZMAT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AND SUSPECT THER HAULED ACID AND CAUSTIC IN IT WITHOUT CLEANING THE UNIT BETWEEN LOADS. WE WERE PROVIED A WASHOUT TICKET WHEN THEY RETURNED IT AND WE NEVER QUESTIONED THE INTEGRITY OF THE UNIT PRIOR TO HAULING THE FERRIC CHLORIDE SOLUTION.

column168: A RELEASE OF APPROCIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF REGULAR UNLEADED GASOLINE OCCURED DURING A TRANSFER FROM A TANKER TRUCK TO AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK (UST).  THE UST WAS OVERFILLED RESULTING IN FUEL BACKING UP INTO THE CONTAINMENT SUMP SURROUNDING THE TANK FILL PORT AND SUBSEQUENTLY SPILLING OUT TO THE CONCRETE PAD COVERING THE UST.  UPON RELEASE TO THE CONCRETE TANK PAD, THE FUEL MIGRATED OVER PAVEMENT TOWARDS AND INTO A CATCH BASIN LOCATED APPROXIMATELY 30 FEET FROM THE UST FILL PORT.  PERSONNEL FROM THE CARRIER (F.L. ROBERTS & COMPANY) AND THE DESTINATION FACILITY (WESTERN NEW ENGLAND UNIVERSITY) INITIATED RESPONSE ACTIONS CONSISTING OF APPLYING ABSORBENT MATERIAL (SPEEDY DRY AND SAND) TO THE RELEASE AREA, POSITIONING OF A BERM OF ABOSRBENT MATERIAL AROUND THE CATCH BASIN, AND PLACING ABSORBENT WITHIN THE CATCH BASIN.

column168: CON-WAY FREIGHT CONTACTED ERTS TO RESPOND TO A ROLLOVER ACCIDENT RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF UP TO 600 GALLONS OF UN1824 SODIUM HYDROXIDE WHICH IMPACTED THE ROADWAY AND ADJACENT SOIL.  THE AREA WAS DESCRIBED AS A WETLAND AND THE RELASED PRODUCT WAS APPEARED TO BE REACTING WITH THE MOISTURE ON THE GROUND.  THE TOTES WERE LOCATED ON THE REAR TRAILER WHICH WAS ON ITS SIDE.  THE LEAD TRAILER WAS UPRIGHT AND WAS LEAKING AN UNKNOWN LIQUID.  AT 0854 ET, IDEM WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.  NO INCIDENT NUMBER IS AVAILABLE AT THAT TIME.  AT 0858 ET, THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE AND ISSUED TRACKING NUMBER 1054087.  ERTS HAS DISPATCHED A NETWORK CONTRACTOR TO THE SITE WITH AN ETA OF 30 MINUTES.  THE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED ONSIDE AND INSPECTED THE RELEASE.  THEY REPORTED THE OTHE RMATERIAL INVOLVED WAS AN AMINE.    THE CONTRACTOR STATED APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF THE AMINES HAD BEEN RELEASED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE TRAILER WAS TRANSPORTED TO A NEARBY TERMINAL TO BE CLEANED BY FACILITY PERSONNEL.  APPROXIMATELY 25-50 GALLONS OF THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE HAD BEEN RELEASED TO THE ROADWAY AND SOIL.  NO PRODUCT HAD REACHED THE WETLAND.  THE CARGO REMAINING IN THE TRAILER WAS PREVENTING THE DOOR FROM BEING OPENED.  THE CONTRACTOR ATTEMPTED TO GET ACCESS TO THE INTERIOR.    THE CONTRACTOR GAINED ACCESS TO THE TRAILER AND REPORTED THE TOTES WERE CONSTRUCTED OF METAL AND RELEASED PRODUCT FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICES.  THEY TRANSLOADED THE CARGO ONTO A REPLACEMENT TRAILER AND DECONTAMINATED THE IMPACTED AREA.  THE CONTAMINATED SOILS MEAURE APPROXIMATELY 50'X 80' AND NEEDED TO BE EXCAVATED AT A LATER TIME.  RICK HENKLE WITH IDEM REQUESTED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL BE SCRAPED TO REMOVE THE RELEASED MATERIA.  THE CONTRACTOR UTILIZED A SKID STEER TO REMOVE THE SOIL.  THE CONTRACTOR STATED THE TRAILER HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE SITE.  THE CONTRACTOR COMPLETED THE CLEANUP AND DEPARTED THE SITE.

column168: THE DRIVER LEFT THE TERMINAL AFTER LOADING. HE WAS DRIVING TO HIS FIRST FUEL DELIVERY. WHILE TURNING ON TO U.S. 31 FROM SHADES CREEK PARKWAY, EXECUTING A RIGHT TURN NORTH ON TO U.S. 31 THE DRIVER TURNED TOO SHARP AND STRUCK THE GUARDRAIL. THE PIPING AT THE SCULLY GAUGE DEVELOPED A SLIGHT LEAK DUE TO THE STRIKE. THE PIPE WAS LOOSENED ENOUGH FOR THE FUEL IN THE LINE TO LEAK. THE LEAK DURATION WAS APPROXIMATELY 30-40 MINUTES. THE FD DEPLOYED ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND APPLIED A STOP LEAK COMPOUND TO THE PIPE.
column169: THE MCPHERSON COMPANIES, INC. (TMC) HAS MOVED ALL FUTURE ROUTES FROM THE TERMINAL TO THIS DELIVERY LOCATION TO VALLEY ROAD, THUS ELIMINATING THIS ROUTE. THE DRIVE RECIEVED COACHING, A LONG WITH ALL OF THE OTHER FUEL DRIVERS, ABOUT BEING AWARE OF THEIR SURROUNDINGS. THE ROUTE CHANGE WAS APPROVED AND IMPLEMENTED 7/24/2013. THE COACHING/TRAINING OCCURED ON 7/31/2013.

column168: UNLOADING AT CUSTOMER LOCATION INSIDE RECESSED RECEIVING DOCK. UNLOADING PROCESS STOPPED TO TAKE A SAMPLE OF THE MATERIAL BEING DELIVERED. DURING PROCESS STOPPAGE TIME, HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION GRAVITY FEED INTO THE COMPRESSED AIR SYSTEM EMPLOYED FOR THE UNLOADING PROCESS. HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION WAS RELEASED FROM THE COMPRESSED AIR LINE ON THE TANK TRAILER WHEN THE COMPRESSED AIR UNIT WAS SHUTDOWN FOR SAMPLING DUE TO IT BYPASSING A CHECKVALVE IN THE SYSTEM. THE COMPRESSED AIR VALVE WAS CLOSED TO STOP THE RELEASE UPON ITS IDENTIFICATION.  ESTIMATE OF RELEASE WAS 25 GALLONS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION (RQ=5000LBS)  ESTIMATE RELEASE TIMEWAS A COUPLE OF MINUTES.  USE OF NEUTRALIZING AGENTS AND DIKING MINIMIZED THE IMPACT OF THE RELEASE.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING WAS IMPLEMENTED. INCREASED INSPECTIONS OF ALL UNLOADING EQUIPMENT. FLEET INSPECTION OF ALL CHECKVALVES. NEW PROCEDURE PUT IN PLACE FOR UNLOADING AT THIS CUSTOMER.

DRIVER WAS NORTHBOUND ON HWY 59 IN WASHINGTON COUNTY, CO WHEN HE LOST CONTROL ON A CURVE AND VEERED UP IN THE NORTH LANE ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY. COLORADO STATE PATROL WAS NOTIFIED AND ARRIVED WITHIN 10-15 MINUTES AND TOOK CONTROL OF THE ACCIDENT SCENE. COLORADO DOT AND EASTERN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE INC. WERE NOTIFIED AND AROUND ARRIVED THE FOLLOWING MORNING. SOME OF THE TOTE’S OF ACCIDENTAL WERE LEAKING ON PORTIONS AND MATERIAL WAS PUMPED INTO A NEW TANKS BY CUSTOM ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES. THE ENVIRONMENTAL FIRM PUMPED A 150 GALLONS OF FUEL FROM THE FUEL TANKS OF THE VEHICLE. THE SITE WAS SECURED AND EASTERN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RETURNED THE FOLLOWING MORNING (JULY 27). AFTER COMPLETING A SITE SAFETY BRIEFING, THE CREW FROM THE ENVIRONMENTAL FIRM PUT ON PROPER PROTECTION GEAR AND BEGAN CLEAN UP OF THE AFFECTED TRUCK AND TRAILER WORE REMOVAL FROM THE SITE. CLEANUP CONTINUED ON JULY 28 AND JULY 31 BEFORE THE WORK WAS FINISHED ON AUGUST 2.
column169: SINCE THE ACCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY DRIVER ERROR, THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED AND FOLLOW UP MEETINGS WITH THE DRIVER WERE CONDUCTED WITH A SAFETY CONSULTANT AND THE SAFEY DIRECTOR. A SAFETY SEMINAR FOR ALL DRIVERS WAS SCHEDULED AND TOOK PLACE ON SEPTEMBER 17, 2013. THE SEMINAR INCLUDED INSTRUCTIONS ON ACCIDENT MISTAKES, DRIVER ERROR AND ACCIDENT ASSURANCE.

column168: BETWEEN 9:00 AM AND 10:00 AM ON JULY 21, 2013, A RELEASE OF DILUTED HCI (THE MATERIAL) OCCURRED NEAR EXIT 49 OF INTERSTATE 70 WESTBOUND IN SMITHTON, PA. THE QUANTITY OF MATERIAL RELEASED IS ESTIMATED AT LESS THAN 100-GALLONS. THE MATERIAL WAS IN TRANSPORT BY A HALLIBURTON CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE (CTMV) (TRUCK #12012598, TRAILER #11630623) AT THE TIME OF INCIDENT. THE MATERIAL RELEASED FROM THE CTMV IMPACTED APPROXIMATELY 100 YARDS OF ASPHALT AND GRAVEL ALONG EXIT 49 OF I-70. AVAILABLE INFORMATION INDICATES THAT THE MATERIAL RELEASED FROM THE CTMV TO THE ROADWAY DID NOT ENTER WATERWAYS OR CONVEYANCE SYSTEMS.    THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NRC ON JULY 21, 2013, UNDER INCIDENT NUMBER 1054597 AND PADEP REGION V OFFICE WITH NO INCIDENT NUMBER.    HALLIBURTON'S INITIAL INCIDENT ASSESSMENT INDICATED THAT A VALVE ON THE CTMV MAY HAVE MALFUNCTIONED, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF DILUTED HCI FROM THE CTMV WHILE IN TRANSIT. HALLIBURTON REMOVED THE CTMV FROM SERVICE AND QUARANTINED IT AT ONE OF ITS SECURE FACILITIES UNTIL FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND TO PERFORM NECESSARY REPAIRS. ADDITIONAL INVESTIGATION AND ASSESSMENTS HAVE BEEN CONDUCTED AND SUPPORT THE INITIAL INCIDENT ASSESSMENT. VERY LITTLE CORROSION IS EVIDENT ON THE CTMV AND ALL EVIDENCE INDICATES THAT THE "FLAPPER VALVE BOTTOM PIN" FOR THE REAR CTMV TANK COMPARTMENT FAILED IN TRANSPORT AND THE HCI RELEASED FROM THE FLAPPER VALVE. THE PIN WAS NOT FOUND OR RECOVERED AT THE SCENE.
column169: IMMEDIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS OCCURRED ON JULY 21, 2013, INCLUDING:    - HALLIBURTON INITIATED EMERGENCY RESPONSE WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF LOCAL CONTRACTED EMERGENCY RESPONDERS;    - LOCAL AUTHORITIES (FIRE DEPARTMENT, POLICE, AND PENNDOT) RESPONDED TO SCENE;    - LOCAL AUTHROITIES CLOSED ALL LANES OF 1-70 FOR APPROXIMATELY 4 HOURS WHILE EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIONS OCCURRED;    - EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIONS ON-SITE INCLUDED PLUGGING A POTENTIALLY MALFUNCTIONING VALVE ON THE CTMV AND REMOVING ANY STANDING LIQUIDS THROUGH USE OF ABSORBENTS, INCLUDING THE APPLICATION OF SODA ASH TO SPILLED MATERIALS;    - HALLIBURTON'S EMERGENCY RESPONDERS PUMPED THE REMAINING CONTENTS TO ANOTHER CTMV; AND     - HALLIBURTON'S EMERGENCY RESPONDERS COLLECTED, DRUMMED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF WASTE MATERIALS FROM ON-SITE EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIVITIES (E.G., NEUTRALIZED ABSORBENTS, ETC.).    ADDITIONAL CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FOLLOWING INCIDENT:    SIMILARLY CONSTRUCTED CTMV TANKS USED IN THIS CAPACITY (HCI TRANSPORT) BY HALLIBURTON - NORTHEAST AREA HAVE BEEN INSPECTED BY QUALIFIED PERSONNEL AND ANY POTENTIAL DEFICIENCIES HAVE BEEN APPROPRIATELY CORRECTED.    ADDITIONALLY, THE CTMV INVOLVED IN INCIDENT WILL BE FULLY REPAIRED AND TESTED PRIOR TO BEING RETURNED INTO SERVICE.

column168: The freight having been offered in Unalakleet, AK as a non-hazardous material shipment a warehouse worker noticed possible hazardous materials labels on a prebuilt and shrink-wrapped pallet.  Upon further investigation, it was determined that there were hazardous material labels present.    During investigation, we found undeclared hazardous materials.  Immediatly following, I contacted Jeff Deitz of the FAA.    None of the shipping documents noted a hazardous material and was signed stating to that fact.    Also found in the shipment:    7 lbs total of smokeless powder, (NA3178)  Approximately 7 small boxes of primers, cap type, (UN0044)  Significant amounts of cartridges, small arms, (UN0012)  Flammable liquids and, (UN unknown but package noted FLAMMABLE)  Matches, safety (UN1944)
column169: We have had discussions with the Unalakleet, AK office on enhancing awareness for the presence of undeclared hazardous materials.    A couple of these points were to ask many questions of the shipper regardless of commodity and the inspection enhancement of household shipments to  include holding these shipments until sufficiently inspected.

On July 29th at around 1445,a TSA screener from the TSA WEST contacted AA UDG, (Undeclared Dangerous Goods) room rep. Ana Ortiz to respond to an alarm on an item found in the check bag of passenger Anderson Novalin, tag bag #19-13-78.  The bag was in transit from Port Au Prince Haiti to Baltimore Maryland.  The bag was in the process of being screened  inside the TSA West room when the incident began.   Ana determined that the bag had a foul smell and an unknown substance had spilled inside the bag.  Ana did not remove the item and contact AA Compliance Coordinator, Carolann Rodriguez.  At 1450 the CC responded and located the bag outside the TSA West screening room on the ramp between D24/D25.    An AA Environmental Coordinator was contacted.  In addition the passenger was called at the departure gate to gather information as to the contents of his bag.  The TSA contacted the Metro Dade Fire Rescue and Hazmat Team.  They reponded at app. 1520 and contained the area.  The liquid in the bag was tested by the Metro Dade Hazmat team and reported to be Malathion a toxic pesticide, by Chief Williams.   The Incident began app 1450 and concluded about 1750.
column169: This case is currently under investigation by the FAA/DOT.  I would however recommend that the govt. of Haiti ensure proper screening of outbound passengers for Undeclared Hazmat.
